    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the brake pads are still in good condition, the sound could be coming from other components. One possibility is that the brake caliper's slide pins or piston seals are worn out, causing the caliper to vibrate and produce a high-pitched squeal. It's also possible that the rotors themselves are warped or uneven, which can cause the brake pads to vibrate and produce a squealing noise. \n\nYou might also want to check the brake caliper's mounting hardware, such as the caliper bolts or the brake rotor retaining clips, to see if they're loose or corroded. If the hardware is loose or damaged, it can cause the caliper to move around and produce unusual noises when braking. \n\nIt's also worth noting that some modern vehicles, including the 2018 Toyota Camry, have a feature called \"brake pad wear sensors\" that can detect when the brake pads are worn down and alert the driver. However, these sensors can sometimes malfunction and produce unusual noises, even if the brake pads are still in good condition.",
